    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nAfter the change made by #38509 , new buffers can only be opened by following `switchbuf`, losing the ability to specify a different option based on different key bind, etc.\n\nNote that temporarily changing `switchbuf` around the call does not work as the actual buffer opening operation takes place in a callback:\n```lua\n-- attempting to override `switchbuf = usetab` does not work \nvim.keymap.set(\"n\", \"gf\", function()\n\tlocal old_switchbuf = vim.o.switchbuf\n\tvim.o.switchbuf = \"usetab\"\n\tvim.lsp.buf.definition()\n\tvim.o.switchbuf = old_switchbuf\nend, opts)\n```\n\nThe only viable solution is to override `opts.on_list` manually. Although the default implementation of `opts.on_list` isn't that complicated, this does introduce quite a bit of friction coming from the old `reuse_win` approach especially considering the default handler isn't exposed as a standalone function that can be invoked.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAdd `opts.switchbuf` to allow the buffer opening behaviour to be overridden briefly such that passing `{ reuse_win = true }` is equivalent to `{ switchbuf = \"usetab\" }`",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Removing `reuse_win` was intended to remove options, so adding a new option isn't attractive.\n\nIn various issues/PRs we have discussed a more generic approach, which is for lsp features to have a promise/future interface:\n\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/22598#issuecomment-1463367606\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/31206\n\nsome progress was made in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/34523 but got stalled.\n\nMeanwhile, for the most urgent use-cases, we have provided some `on_foo` callbacks such as [on_list](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/af707dd24261f34a72ba7bbea5cf2e802f81837d/runtime/doc/lsp.txt#L1332) and [on_jump](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/af707dd24261f34a72ba7bbea5cf2e802f81837d/runtime/doc/diagnostic.txt#L191) , so that users can do arbitrary things before/after an action occurs. That's a stop-gap until the generalized \"promise\" interface is achieved.",
