            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I don't think so. Because `switchbuf` is supposed to control the behaviour of one buffer switching action, and the goal here is to be able to dynamically change the buffer switching action per usage.\n\nLet me expand on the use cases a bit more:\n\n## Use case quick fix navigation\nWhen viewing entries on the quick fix list, I would like the same window to be used all the time regardless if the same buffer is opened elsewhere. Therefore, I set `switchbuf=uselast`.\n\n## Use case LSP .cpp/.h editing\nWhen I edit x.cpp and x.h side by side (or in their own tabs) and activate jump to definition, I want the cursor to jump to the corresponding location in the other window.\nPreviously, this could be done via `vim.lsp.buf.definition({ reuse_win = true })`. And the behaviour is equivalent to `switchbuf=usetab`.\n\n## Use case LSP multi tab editing\nSome times, I have the same set of files opened in multiple tabs, where each tab functions as a workspace. I want to jump to definition using the current window instead of messing around with windows in other tabs.\nPreviously, this could be done via `vim.lsp.buf.definition({ reuse_win = false })`. And the behaviour is equivalent to `switchbuf=uselast`.\n\n## Summary\nEssentially, I want to be able to control how I switch to a buffer depending on my use cases per action. This can be achieved by just changing the value of `switchbuf` on invoke and then restore it. This has worked pretty well in other parts of my scripts, but it does not work with LSP because it uses a callback. To make it work, `reuse_win` must be changed around when the callback is invoked and not where `vim.lsp.buf.definition` is called.\n\nI understand that we want to avoid adding more flags. So I have two suggestions:\n\n### Options 1\nMake an exception for `switchbuf` and allow it to be on `vim.lsp.ListOpts`. My justification are:\n1. `loclist` is also on there, and that flag is also passed directly to the default on_list handler. So having another flag that's also passed directly to the default handler isn't that out of place. \n2. `reuse_win` was supported. When a handy flag like this is deprecated, a simple alternative should be provided so the migration can be very simple. With this option, one can easily migrate `vim.lsp.buf.definition({ reuse_win = true })` to `vim.lsp.buf.definition({ switchbuf = \"usetab\" })`.\n\n### Option 2\nAllow the default on_list handler to be exposed as `vim.lsp.buf.on_list`. This allows users to augment the default on_list without having to duplicate the source code. Allowing the migration to be somewhat simple.\n`vim.lsp.buf.definition({ reuse_win = true })` to \n```lua\nvim.lsp.buf.definition({ on_list = function(opt)\n\tlocal old_switchbuf = vim.o.switchbuf\n\tvim.o.switchbuf = \"usetab\"\n\tvim.lsp.buf.on_list(opt)\n\tvim.o.switchbuf = old_switchbuf\nend})\n```",
